122Kg 10:33 east of the Jordan, as far south as the town of Aroer on the Arnon River - this included the territories of Gilead and Bashan, where the tribes of Gad, Reuben, and East Manasseh lived. 
122Kg 10:34 Everything else that Jehu did, including his brave deeds, is recorded in The History of the Kings of Israel.
122Kg 10:35 He died and was buried in Samaria, and his son Jehoahaz succeeded him as king. 
122Kg 10:36 Jehu had ruled in Samaria as king of Israel for twenty-eight years. 
122Kg 11:1 As soon as King Ahaziah's mother Athaliah learned of her son's murder, she gave orders for all the members of the royal family to be killed. 
122Kg 11:2 Only Ahaziah's son Joash escaped. He was about to be killed with the others, but was rescued by his aunt Jehosheba, who was King Jehoram's daughter and Ahaziah's half sister. She took him and his nurse into a bedroom in the Temple and hid him from Athaliah, so that he was not killed. 
122Kg 11:3 For six years Jehosheba took care of the boy and kept him hidden in the Temple, while Athaliah ruled as queen. 
122Kg 11:4 But in the seventh year Jehoiada the priest sent for the officers in charge of the royal bodyguard and of the palace guards, and told them to come to the Temple, where he made them agree under oath to what he planned to do. He showed them King Ahaziah's son Joash 
122Kg 11:5 and gave them the following orders�� "When you come on duty on the Sabbath, one third of you are to guard the palace; 
122Kg 11:6 another third are to stand guard at the Sur Gate, and the other third are to stand guard at the gate behind the other guards. 
122Kg 11:7 The two groups that go off duty on the Sabbath are to stand guard at the Temple to protect the king. 
